The democracy movement in Latin America will be stronger, as the support of private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than the unemployment.
In many parts of the region is the influence of Brazil is greater than that of the United States.
These results, the Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by the Economist.
This survey will be carried out on a regular basis since 1995 and shows the exchange of opinions in This region.
Two facts in this year's poll in September and october, particularly in's eye.
First, the good mood in Latin America
And secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its key institutions.
In many countries of the South Pacific coast has increased the democratic movement here (Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy is growing at an annual rate of around 6% since 2002, the number of democracy advocates from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
In Mexico, where the economy since the sharp fall In the last year, is such a trend.
But only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the world's two most populous countries in the region, which, the regional average (. graph 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said that they will be with the country's democratic practice. As many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (graph 3).
About 34% trust Congress and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but a sharp increase from 2003 (17% or 24%).
Latin American economic crises A decade ago undermined the efforts to bring about more democracy.
Also during the world economic crisis, it may be that the countries of Latin America only a brief recession, and have recovered quickly.
In addition, the poor through a stronger social network.
(According to reports from the u. n. Economic Commission for Latin America this week, 2009, the poverty rate in Latin America only slightly, and has fallen this year at 32%.)
But there are strong differences from country to country (s. graph 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread progress thinking.
In Mexico and Central America, where the recession mount was increased violence and crime, this is less the case.
Only the second time since the beginning of the see many respondents in Latin America in the crime in their country a bigger problem than the unemployment (s. graph 5).
Some 31% say that either they or a family member last year, victims of a crime. But compared to 38% last year dropped the values and the lowest level since 1995.
The rising economic performance is reflected in the strong support of the private sector and the market economy: around 71% of respondents at said that the private sector for the development, in 2007 there were 56% (s. graph 6).
Approximately 58% said that only the market economy can bring their country progress, compared with 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela this view (and 80% are maintained for a private sector), although their leftist President, Hugo Chávez, nationalized many private companies.
Brazil has had 19% of respondents (18% last year), the largest weight in the region, followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared with 11% last year).
The respondents in Mexico and most Central American countries, on the other hand, the most influential country in the United states, and this role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua and Venezuela.
