Snow and ice: 24 departments in orange alert
The snow episodes are still transport difficulties, especially in the secondary transport networks of Brittany and to affect various economic activities.
Twenty-four departments are now in orange alert due to the threat of snow and ice.
The regions, et Loir, Deux Sèvres and drive have been added to the already in Orange alert, 20 departments; 18 since Wednesday afternoon and two, the Dordogne and the Gironde, then later in the night.
According to Météo France, affect the intensive snow showers in the north of the Gironde and the Charentes, it is snowing lightly on the Ile de France.
In the regions affected by snow blankets from 2 to 5 cm, expected in some places from 7 to 10 cm and 1 cm by 3 cm, even up to 5 cm in the Paris region.
The regions Charente, Charente-Maritime, coasts d Armor, Finistère, Gironde, Dordogne, Poitou and the regions Basse Normandy, Ile de France and Limousin.
The snow are significant enough to cause transport disabilities and certain economic activities, says Météo France.
In the region coasts d Armor are blocked several Regional links for the heavy traffic of about 7.5 tonnes, including the routes Guingamp Lannion and Saint Brieuc Loudéac.
The transport situation of secondary transport networks in Brittany, according to the traffic policemen who advise against using their own vehicle only in Notfalle, very difficult, and the use of some TER coaches was deleted the entire day.
In Picardy was lifted the school transport for Thursday.
For the heavy traffic have been scheduled on Wednesday evening, no specific restrictive measures.
The police "calls for the drivers to exercise the utmost caution on the roads and the corresponding adapt their driving to."
The Directorate General of civil aviation (DGAC) called for the airlines on Thursday, 25% of the Paris airport Roissy and 10% of the Orly flights from flights due to the expected to remove heavy snow.
The DGAB recommends The airline passengers to contact their airline.
The Gatwick airports in the south of London and the airport in Edinburgh, scotland, are closed until Thursday morning.
